1
00:01:38,700 --> 00:01:41,099
Hey... What's that song?

2
00:01:42,900 --> 00:01:47,180
Cut! Cut!
Who let that creep in here?

3
00:01:48,500 --> 00:01:49,979
Spongers!

4
00:01:50,180 --> 00:01:53,780
Throw him the hell out of here!
What do we pay you for?

5
00:02:01,299 --> 00:02:04,780
SERGEI BODROV

6
00:02:06,180 --> 00:02:09,379
-Your name?
- Bagrov.

7
00:02:11,099 --> 00:02:12,979
Danila Sergeyevich.

8
00:02:13,180 --> 00:02:16,579
Born 1975.
Station Street, 22.

9
00:02:18,900 --> 00:02:23,579
- Place of work?
- Haven't finished being demobbed yet.

10
00:02:28,180 --> 00:02:31,780
-Where did you serve?
- In the army.

11
00:02:33,180 --> 00:02:37,579
-Want to work for us?
- No.

12
00:02:43,099 --> 00:02:46,979
You broke their security guy's arm.
And nearly took his eye out.

13
00:02:47,379 --> 00:02:50,300
If you'd been drunk,
I'd have arrested you.

14
00:02:51,300 --> 00:02:52,780
Get outta here!

15
00:02:54,699 --> 00:02:58,579
If you don't get a job within a week,
I'll put you on probation.

16
00:03:05,099 --> 00:03:08,780
VIKTOR SUKHORUKOV

17
00:03:28,699 --> 00:03:31,979
I really broke his arm?

18
00:03:33,500 --> 00:03:35,579
No. Just dislocated it.

19
00:03:41,300 --> 00:03:46,180
And that guy who was screaming?
Who is he?

20
00:03:47,500 --> 00:03:48,979
The director.

21
00:03:57,699 --> 00:04:03,180
-And what was that song?
- ''Wings'' by Nautilus.

22
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:14,099
SVETLANA PISMICHENKO

23
00:04:16,699 --> 00:04:20,699
Sergei Bagrov,
born 1942,

24
00:04:20,899 --> 00:04:22,779
...repeat convictions for burglary.

25
00:04:23,779 --> 00:04:26,779
He was killed in a prison camp
in January '82.

26
00:04:29,699 --> 00:04:31,579
He was my classmate.

27
00:04:34,100 --> 00:04:37,899
YURI KUZNETSOV

28
00:04:39,500 --> 00:04:43,180
Do you have ''Wings'' by Nautilus?
The CD?

29
00:04:47,379 --> 00:04:51,300
Whadda you want? Get out of here,
or I'll call the police.

30
00:04:54,699 --> 00:04:57,779
VYACHESLAV BUTUSOV

31
00:05:04,699 --> 00:05:07,579
You could at least chop wood
ratherthan sticking your neck out.

32
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:09,980
Would have been betterto stay
in the army.

33
00:05:10,180 --> 00:05:12,379
Here they'll probably kill you,
idiot.

34
00:05:12,699 --> 00:05:15,579
Always turning on that metal of yours.

35
00:05:17,899 --> 00:05:21,579
You'll croak in prison
like your good-for-nothing father.

36
00:05:25,699 --> 00:05:30,100
The only hope I have
is my little Viktor.

37
00:05:30,300 --> 00:05:34,980
He's a big man there, you know,
in Leningrad.

38
00:05:45,180 --> 00:05:50,579
Just look at these. So little.
How cute you all were.

39
00:05:50,779 --> 00:05:53,980
-Just look.
- I've seen them.

40
00:05:54,180 --> 00:05:55,779
Take another look.

41
00:05:57,100 --> 00:06:00,980
You had better go to your brother
in Leningrad.

42
00:06:02,699 --> 00:06:07,180
I'll die soon, you know,
and he's to you like father now.

43
00:06:07,500 --> 00:06:09,379
This is your blood.

44
00:06:09,699 --> 00:06:13,379
The closest person to you
in this world.

45
00:06:15,100 --> 00:06:16,980
My little Viktor.

46
00:06:21,699 --> 00:06:27,300
BROTHER

47
00:06:28,500 --> 00:06:31,779
If you haven't seen Moscow,
you haven't seen much.

48
00:06:36,100 --> 00:06:39,579
The Chechen was released.
We need to take him out.

49
00:06:40,379 --> 00:06:42,300
He grabbed the whole market.

50
00:06:42,500 --> 00:06:45,899
Says it was his.
He's collecting from our spots.

51
00:06:46,100 --> 00:06:49,579
At the meet we agreed all peaceful,
like our people don't want war.

52
00:06:49,779 --> 00:06:52,779
But he and Paramon are close...

53
00:06:53,980 --> 00:06:56,379
The Chechen's going down!

54
00:06:59,100 --> 00:07:00,980
In short, fifteen.

55
00:07:03,500 --> 00:07:06,579
You know me. My prices are fair.

56
00:07:08,100 --> 00:07:09,980
Fifteen...

57
00:07:10,379 --> 00:07:16,100
That's good money, of course,
but forthe Chechen...

58
00:07:17,980 --> 00:07:19,899
With him I'm risking my skull.

59
00:07:22,100 --> 00:07:25,899
- How much?
- Twenty. And ten up front.

60
00:07:41,300 --> 00:07:43,180
You get a week for prepwork.

61
00:07:45,779 --> 00:07:47,579
Two.

62
00:07:50,899 --> 00:07:52,779
The Tatar's becoming a wiseguy.

63
00:07:53,699 --> 00:07:55,579
He took a lot up front.

64
00:07:56,500 --> 00:08:00,379
You guys hang up at the market day
and night, and keep out of sight.

65
00:08:01,699 --> 00:08:05,980
Bite off more than you can chew
and you wind up in the zoo.

66
00:09:45,500 --> 00:09:49,379
- Do you have ''Wings'' by Nautilus?
- No. They go quickly.

67
00:09:49,700 --> 00:09:52,580
But you stop in again. We should get
another shipment.

68
00:09:53,500 --> 00:09:56,379
- Have you anything else?
- Of course.

69
00:09:58,100 --> 00:10:03,379
Here's ''Titanic on the Fontanka''
with Grebenschikov.

70
00:10:03,700 --> 00:10:06,379
And this is ''Ten-year Report''

71
00:10:07,179 --> 00:10:09,580
Their best songs covered by friends.

72
00:10:09,779 --> 00:10:11,580
How much they cost?

73
00:10:11,779 --> 00:10:14,779
This one's 75,800. The other one's
78,000.

74
00:11:12,299 --> 00:11:14,580
Well, what we selling, wino?

75
00:11:17,179 --> 00:11:19,179
You got watches?

76
00:11:19,379 --> 00:11:21,580
Well, my cut's fifty now.

77
00:11:21,779 --> 00:11:24,779
From you, you fucking worm, I said!

78
00:11:25,500 --> 00:11:28,379
And what did you think?
Taxes.

79
00:11:28,700 --> 00:11:33,299
- But I haven't sold anything yet!
- I'm confiscating the goods.

80
00:11:33,700 --> 00:11:38,179
But, sonny, ljust...
I haven't sold anything yet.

81
00:11:38,899 --> 00:11:42,179
- I haven't sold anything!
-What's the difference?

82
00:12:02,700 --> 00:12:05,580
The city?
The city's a frightening force.

83
00:12:05,779 --> 00:12:07,980
And the biggerthe city,
the stronger it is.

84
00:12:08,179 --> 00:12:12,580
It sucks you in.
Only the strong can climb out.

85
00:12:14,500 --> 00:12:16,100
And even so...

86
00:12:23,100 --> 00:12:26,379
-What's your name?
- Hoffman.

87
00:12:26,700 --> 00:12:29,980
-What are you, a Jew?
- I'm German.

88
00:12:30,179 --> 00:12:33,179
Oh... I'm not wild about Jews...

89
00:12:33,500 --> 00:12:36,379
-And Germans?
- Germans? They're okay.

90
00:12:36,700 --> 00:12:39,580
-What's the difference?
-Why you badgering me about it?

91
00:12:44,899 --> 00:12:48,379
-Where have you taken me?
- My homeland.

92
00:12:49,980 --> 00:12:52,100
My ancestors lie here.

93
00:12:57,700 --> 00:12:59,379
Sit down.

94
00:13:04,299 --> 00:13:07,179
- Here.
- Hold on.

95
00:13:07,779 --> 00:13:09,779
What?

96
00:13:09,980 --> 00:13:14,179
I brought a present for my brother.
I guess it wasn't to be.

97
00:13:23,379 --> 00:13:25,299
Oh, gimme some of that...

98
00:13:37,779 --> 00:13:40,179
She's a doll.

99
00:13:40,700 --> 00:13:43,299
Hey, girl, what's your name?

100
00:13:47,700 --> 00:13:49,299
Tickets, please.

101
00:13:50,500 --> 00:13:52,379
No ticket.

102
00:13:52,700 --> 00:13:54,580
Tickets, please.

103
00:13:58,100 --> 00:13:59,980
No ticket.

104
00:14:00,779 --> 00:14:02,580
Your tickets, please.

105
00:14:02,899 --> 00:14:05,580
Listen, you Russian or what?

106
00:14:05,779 --> 00:14:08,299
I'm saying to you in Russian:
no ticket.

107
00:14:08,500 --> 00:14:10,580
Then pay the fine, please.

108
00:14:10,779 --> 00:14:13,580
What fine, huh?
I'm an invalid.

109
00:14:15,100 --> 00:14:17,580
You pay the fine or show me
your ticket.

110
00:14:17,779 --> 00:14:22,379
Hey, take a load off your feet.
Sit down.

111
00:14:22,700 --> 00:14:25,580
Well, if you haven't got tickets,
then you have to pay the fine.

112
00:14:28,700 --> 00:14:31,379
Hey, don't you understand?

113
00:14:34,700 --> 00:14:36,179
Come on, come on.

114
00:14:36,779 --> 00:14:38,779
Pay the fine!

115
00:14:41,980 --> 00:14:43,779
Brother, don't kill me!

116
00:14:44,100 --> 00:14:46,980
The money,
take it all, take it!

117
00:14:47,179 --> 00:14:49,179
Don't kill me, brother!

118
00:14:51,299 --> 00:14:54,379
You're not my brother,
you blackassed worm!

119
00:14:57,179 --> 00:14:59,700
- How much is the fine?
- Seven.

120
00:15:03,299 --> 00:15:04,779
Run!

121
00:15:39,100 --> 00:15:44,179
Hey, guys!
It's not ''Nora'', it's ''Norah''.

122
00:15:48,779 --> 00:15:51,379
In short, you know, to get there
you've got to...

123
00:16:03,700 --> 00:16:05,100
Bye!

124
00:16:07,179 --> 00:16:10,580
Man, oh man, that's such a cool
Walkman! Let me listen.

125
00:16:17,980 --> 00:16:21,580
Why you blasting this crap?
Have you got anything decent?

126
00:16:21,779 --> 00:16:24,580
-Are you deaf or something?
- No.

127
00:16:24,779 --> 00:16:28,379
Your Walkman's fine,
but you're dressed like a pig.

128
00:16:28,779 --> 00:16:31,899
You got any acid?
Or dough?

129
00:16:32,100 --> 00:16:34,580
Got any dough?
- No.

130
00:16:34,899 --> 00:16:37,899
I'm Kat.
You can always find me here.

131
00:16:38,100 --> 00:16:41,980
If you get some money, come here
and we'll get stoned. Well, later!

132
00:16:55,100 --> 00:16:56,980
It's open!

133
00:17:12,500 --> 00:17:14,900
On your knees! Hands out!

134
00:17:15,099 --> 00:17:18,099
I'm looking for my brother.
Viktor Bagrov. He lived here.

135
00:17:18,900 --> 00:17:22,099
I'm his younger brother.
Been in Leningrad two days.

136
00:17:22,299 --> 00:17:26,180
My mom gave me his address:
Moika 1, apartment 8.

137
00:17:28,500 --> 00:17:31,579
Well, hello, brother!

138
00:17:36,779 --> 00:17:39,180
It's not Leningrad,
but St. Petersburg.

139
00:17:40,099 --> 00:17:43,700
St. Pete's, for short.
A beautiful city, but a province.

140
00:17:44,700 --> 00:17:48,380
Got to go to Moscow.
All the power's there.

141
00:17:48,700 --> 00:17:51,579
I'll scrape it a little more here,
and then to Moscow.

142
00:17:52,099 --> 00:17:54,980
- How's mom?
- Okay.

143
00:17:59,380 --> 00:18:01,579
Here, she sent you this.

144
00:18:02,900 --> 00:18:07,180
Come on, drink. I still got
some business to take care of.

145
00:18:18,700 --> 00:18:20,579
This'll hold you over for awhile.

146
00:18:23,900 --> 00:18:28,099
Get some nice clothes,
rent an apartment or a room.

147
00:18:30,180 --> 00:18:33,779
Nothing over a hundred for now
and then we'll see.

148
00:18:37,779 --> 00:18:41,579
- How was the army?
- Okay.

149
00:18:43,099 --> 00:18:45,579
Mom wrote that you were in the war.

150
00:18:46,500 --> 00:18:50,579
Nah. I sat things out at HQ.
I was a clerk.

151
00:18:53,980 --> 00:18:56,180
Can you shoot?

152
00:18:56,500 --> 00:18:58,779
Yeah, they took us out
to the shooting range.

153
00:19:08,500 --> 00:19:10,900
Hello.
Do you have ''Wings'' by Nautilus?

154
00:19:12,900 --> 00:19:14,579
Well, just give me what you got.

155
00:20:44,779 --> 00:20:47,579
He's an ex-Chechen terrorist.

156
00:20:47,779 --> 00:20:50,579
They've moved into St. Pete
from Moscow too.

157
00:20:50,779 --> 00:20:52,980
Grabbing up everything, brother.

158
00:20:53,700 --> 00:20:55,180
I already told you about it.

159
00:20:56,500 --> 00:20:59,579
Took this market.
Now he's squeezing Russians out.

160
00:20:59,779 --> 00:21:02,180
And I got a piece of the action there.

161
00:21:02,380 --> 00:21:07,099
So he came down hard. He knows we're
weak now, so he's strangling us.

162
00:21:07,299 --> 00:21:11,779
He bought off everyone there.
And killed the ones he didn't buy up.

163
00:21:11,980 --> 00:21:17,579
And so it's my turn, Danny.
If I don't pay...

164
00:21:22,700 --> 00:21:26,579
So it's either him or us.
That's how it is, brother.

165
00:21:31,299 --> 00:21:33,380
He loves walking around the market
during the day.

166
00:21:33,700 --> 00:21:36,579
Inspects his holdings, the creep.

167
00:21:36,779 --> 00:21:38,779
This is the best place.

168
00:21:38,980 --> 00:21:42,380
His bodyguards are always with him:
two or three guerillas.

169
00:21:42,700 --> 00:21:45,779
All darkies. With rods. Beasts.

170
00:21:47,180 --> 00:21:49,380
All in all, the job's not easy.

171
00:21:49,700 --> 00:21:52,980
You size things up and think
how you'll make your exit.

172
00:21:53,980 --> 00:21:57,299
I'd better give the money to you.
Two thousand bucks.

173
00:21:57,500 --> 00:21:59,779
Don't come to my place anymore,
it's dangerous.

174
00:22:00,380 --> 00:22:02,579
If something comes up, give me a ring.

175
00:22:04,099 --> 00:22:07,299
Here's a barrel and a clip.
That's another six hundred.

176
00:22:07,500 --> 00:22:10,579
-We'll settle up later.
- I'll get by.

177
00:22:38,299 --> 00:22:42,180
Hello. It's us.
The Tatar wasn't there.

178
00:22:49,099 --> 00:22:52,180
- How much for potatoes?
- One and a half.

179
00:24:25,500 --> 00:24:27,380
How's business?

180
00:24:29,099 --> 00:24:30,980
Ah, who cares?

181
00:24:31,700 --> 00:24:35,900
Only that thug and his pals are here,
looking for you.

182
00:24:36,779 --> 00:24:38,980
Listen, German. I need a room.

183
00:24:39,180 --> 00:24:42,180
A small one. Downtown.
In a quiet neighborhood.

184
00:24:42,380 --> 00:24:44,299
Ask your people, okay?

185
00:24:45,900 --> 00:24:47,099
Here.

186
00:24:52,700 --> 00:24:54,180
Thanks.

187
00:24:56,099 --> 00:25:01,180
- Did you find your brother?
- I found him.

188
00:25:20,500 --> 00:25:23,380
-Who is it?
- It's me, Zinka. Open up.

189
00:25:23,779 --> 00:25:29,380
Zinka? Who the heck's Zinka?
Get outta here, whore.

190
00:25:29,700 --> 00:25:33,900
Have you lost your fucking mind, old
man? Open up! It's me, Zinka!

191
00:25:34,099 --> 00:25:37,180
What a fool! His brain's rotted!

192
00:25:38,700 --> 00:25:41,579
-What do you want?
- I brought you a lodger.

193
00:25:45,500 --> 00:25:47,180
Get it out!

194
00:25:51,380 --> 00:25:53,299
People walking around...

195
00:26:05,299 --> 00:26:08,180
So, old man, you got all mangy here
without me?

196
00:28:34,700 --> 00:28:36,579
Hey, you, kind sir!

197
00:28:37,700 --> 00:28:39,299
Buy a watermelon.

198
00:28:41,579 --> 00:28:44,579
- Is it good?
- Sure! Look what a beauty!

199
00:28:45,299 --> 00:28:49,180
-Yesterday I ate 7 of them myself.
- Okay.

200
00:28:49,700 --> 00:28:52,579
- How much?
- Only six thousand.

201
00:28:54,500 --> 00:28:56,900
Thanks. Enjoy it!

202
00:29:41,779 --> 00:29:44,299
Lord! What's going on?

203
00:29:44,500 --> 00:29:46,500
There, the guy with the watermelon!

204
00:31:58,700 --> 00:32:00,180
Maybe you need help, huh?

205
00:32:01,099 --> 00:32:03,980
I'm outta here. Keep driving.
I'll find you.

206
00:32:40,500 --> 00:32:43,380
It wasn't the Tatar. A young guy.

207
00:32:43,980 --> 00:32:46,900
He did everything first class.
A real pro.

208
00:32:47,099 --> 00:32:50,099
The Chechen kicked the bucket,
and that guy just walked off.

209
00:32:50,299 --> 00:32:53,579
He hopped in a yellow tram
and was off.

210
00:32:53,779 --> 00:32:55,779
I winged him, the motherfucker.

211
00:32:55,980 --> 00:32:58,180
But the bitch greased Pinecone.

212
00:32:58,500 --> 00:33:00,380
Pinecone? Whacked him dead?

213
00:33:00,700 --> 00:33:03,299
Don't know. They took him
to the hospital.

214
00:33:03,500 --> 00:33:06,180
Why were you shooting
if it wasn't the Tatar?

215
00:33:06,500 --> 00:33:08,180
Well, you know, I...

216
00:33:08,500 --> 00:33:11,380
It's the Tatar we have to pay.

217
00:33:11,700 --> 00:33:13,579
You shit-for-brains!

218
00:33:21,180 --> 00:33:24,180
But that the new guy whacked
Pinecone is fine.

219
00:33:24,380 --> 00:33:26,099
They won't suspect us.

220
00:33:27,900 --> 00:33:29,579
Well, Tatar!..

221
00:33:30,779 --> 00:33:34,180
His life hangs by a thread,
but he thinks about the bread.

222
00:33:43,099 --> 00:33:44,980
We should take you to the hospital.

223
00:33:45,779 --> 00:33:48,180
I can't go to the hospital, German.

224
00:33:52,299 --> 00:33:57,579
It's okay, German...
We'll get through.

225
00:34:11,780 --> 00:34:14,980
Zinka! Zinka!

226
00:34:16,980 --> 00:34:20,980
If I'd met you outside Kursk
in '43...

227
00:34:21,179 --> 00:34:24,380
- Beat it, old fool. What do you want?
- Come here.

228
00:34:27,099 --> 00:34:30,780
Get some more vodka, strong stuff,

229
00:34:31,780 --> 00:34:36,099
and bandages at the drugstore,
and... streptomycin.

230
00:34:36,699 --> 00:34:39,380
And antibiotics.

231
00:34:48,900 --> 00:34:53,380
And get something for Gramps,
so he stops pestering us.

232
00:34:53,699 --> 00:34:55,179
Okay.

233
00:35:04,699 --> 00:35:06,579
You're a smart man, German.

234
00:35:09,699 --> 00:35:12,579
Tell me: what do we live for?

235
00:35:13,500 --> 00:35:15,780
Well, everyone decides himself.

236
00:35:16,699 --> 00:35:19,579
There's this saying:

237
00:35:20,699 --> 00:35:23,579
''What's good forthe Russian
is death for the German.''

238
00:35:24,780 --> 00:35:26,980
I live to disprove this.

239
00:35:32,179 --> 00:35:34,179
Do you have a gal?

240
00:35:38,300 --> 00:35:40,179
What about Zinka?

241
00:35:42,179 --> 00:35:45,179
It's probably 'cause of her
you took a shot in the eye?

242
00:35:52,699 --> 00:35:54,179
Never mind.

243
00:35:58,099 --> 00:36:00,380
You're a good man, German.

244
00:36:15,500 --> 00:36:17,579
They closed the kiosk downstairs.

245
00:36:54,099 --> 00:36:56,179
Why'd you stop? Let's roll.

246
00:37:04,500 --> 00:37:06,380
